data.title: United States Counties
data.text:
Many Alaskans were unhappy with the name of Wade Hampton census area, which was named for a South Carolina politician who supported oppression during the Civil War and Reconstruction. Dan Gerken reports that the governor has officially changed its name to Kusilvak.

I had Skagway, AK listed as a borough. The Census Bureau's list of county-equivalent units called it a municipality. The Skagway government website has the confusing headline, "Welcome to the Municipality of Skagway Borough." The site seems to vacillate between that description and the simpler "Municipality of Skagway." I'll go with the Census Bureau's version for now.

I checked up on spaces in some of the county names. I found that DeWitt County, IL, spells its name with no space (i.e., not De Witt). The USGS and the Census Bureau both have it wrong. On the other hand, I was wrong about the spaces in some other county names. I am taking the spelling on the county government website as authoritative.

While checking out the pronunciation of the two Coos counties, I discovered that the one in New Hampshire is officially Coös county , with a diaeresis. Coös, NH is something like "coe-ahss", and Coos, OR is "kooze". According to the Census Bureau, Doña Ana county, NM requires a tilde over the n. Most standard U.S. reference works don't show either of these diacritics.

The Consolidation Act, effective 1856-07-01, created a unified government for San Francisco city and county. Many sources say that the city and county are conterminous (or coextensive). They don't always make it clear that the city and county are not separate governmental entities.

The status of Anchorage is municipality. Juneau and Sitka have the status of "city and borough". All three of them are also described as "unified home rule municipalities".

The secondary administrative divisions of the United States are of several types. There are counties, parishes, independent cities, boroughs, census areas, city-and-boroughs, city-and-counties, a district, a municipality, and a town-and-county. The general term for all these types is "county-equivalent units". The list below shows all 3,142 county-equivalent units of the United States, in groups of 25. The County Maps page has links to state maps that show counties.
